    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-04-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-04-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="557"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d557">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/3788</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Thomas W. Lamont</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="16" xml:id="d557fn16">Chairman of American group.</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-04-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 7, 1922</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received April 10.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: Reverting to our conversation of
                    Wednesday concerning the Consortium for the assistance of China, we have deemed
                    it wise to address a private letter to the members of the American Group, to the
                    number of forty or thereabouts as indicated on this letterhead, along the lines
                    of the draft letter enclosed.<note n="17" xml:id="d557fn17">Draft letter not
                        printed; it is identical with the letter from the managing committee to the
                        members of the American group, Apr. 24, 1922 (<hi rend="italic">post</hi>,
                            <ref target="#pg_766">p. 766</ref>), except for the addition of the
                        penultimate paragraph of that letter which incorporates the suggestions of
                        the Secretary expressed in his letter printed <hi rend="italic">infra.</hi>
                    </note> Inasmuch, however, as we quote informally your expression of opinion on
                    this matter, we will not venture to transmit this letter to the members until
                    you have read it and have given us your sanction.</p>
                <p>Assuring you of our continued desire to cooperate with the Department, I am</p>
                <p>Yours sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">T. W. Lamont</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
